04585nam a22007095i 9780801455803DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014558037 a10.7591/97808014558032doi  a(DE-B1597)496409  a(OCoLC)908447619  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306.4 7094852231 aMurphy, Keith M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSwedish Design :bAn Ethnography /cKeith M. Murphy. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b15 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aExpertise: Cultures and Technologies of Knowledge00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Disentangling Swedish Design -- t1. The Diagram of Swedish Design -- t2. Building the Beautiful Home -- t3. In the Design World -- t4. In the Studio -- t5. Displays of Force -- tConclusion. Designing a Social Cosmology -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSwedish designers are noted for producing distinctive and elegant forms; their furniture and household goods have an especially loyal following around the world. Design in Sweden has more than just an aesthetic component, however. Since at least the late nineteenth century, Swedish politicians and social planners have viewed design as a means for advocating and enacting social change and pushing for a more egalitarian social organization. In this book, Keith M. Murphy examines the special relationship between politics and design in Sweden, revealing in particular the cultural meanings this relationship holds for Swedish society.Over the course of fourteen months of research in Stockholm and at other sites, Murphy conducted in-depth interviews with various players involved in the Swedish design industry—designers, design instructors, government officials, artists, and curators—and observed several different design collectives in action. He found that, for Swedes, design is never socially or politically neutral. Even for common objects like furniture and other household goods, design can be labeled "responsible," "democratic," or "ethical"— descriptors that all neatly resonate with the traditional moral tones of Swedish social democracy. Murphy also considers the example of Ikea and its power to politicize perceptions of the everyday world.More broadly, Swedish Design serves as a model for an anthropological approach to the study of design practice, one that accounts for the various ways in which order is purposefully and meaningfully imposed by designers on the domains of human life, and the consequences those impositions have on the social worlds in which they are embedded.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDesignxAnthropological aspectszSweden. 0aEthnologyzSweden. 0aMaterial culturezSwedenxPhilosophy. 4aAnthropology. 4aArt - Contemporary. 4aWest European History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198040uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145580340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801455803423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801455803/original  a978-3-11-065198-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK